63
00:04:35,659 --> 00:04:38,880
the moment, is given by this integral.

64
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:43,665
The argument of the integral is
the probability of finding the state 

65
00:04:43,665 --> 00:04:47,655
Phi_c at position x at the time t

66
00:04:47,655 --> 00:04:52,558
among all states produced by the potential
V from the initial state of Phi_a.

67
00:04:52,558 --> 00:04:57,118
The integration over space-time
reflects the fact that this local

68
00:04:57,118 --> 00:05:01,120
interaction can occur wherever
the potential is present.

69
00:05:02,140 --> 00:05:07,040
To help your intuition, imagine
that the two wave functions Phi_a and

70
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:11,940
Phi_c correspond to free particles
everywhere, except at the place and

71
00:05:11,940 --> 00:05:14,760
time where the potential intervenes.

72
00:05:14,760 --> 00:05:19,660
The initial state Phi_a will
be a superposition of eigenstates

73
00:05:19,660 --> 00:05:24,610
of the free Hamiltonial with
a given set of coefficients.

74
00:05:24,610 --> 00:05:29,530
The potential will change these coefficients
to produce another superposition

75
00:05:29,530 --> 00:05:33,770
of eigenstates with a different
set of coefficients.

76
00:05:33,770 --> 00:05:37,241
The amplitude M is then
just the amplitude of

77
00:05:37,241 --> 00:05:41,339
the final state Phi_c,
which contains the new mixture.

78
00:05:44,559 --> 00:05:49,130
The invariant amplitude M contains
all the dynamics of a reaction,

79
00:05:49,130 --> 00:05:52,830
Thus the whole physics of the type
