86
00:06:11,760 --> 00:06:13,680
e^2 which is very
much smaller than one.

87
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:22,364
The invariant amplitude is then given by
an integral over the product of the 

88
00:06:22,364 --> 00:06:27,160
four-potential of the target, and

89
00:06:27,160 --> 00:06:32,226
the current density j_µ of
the projectile.

90
00:06:34,451 --> 00:06:38,734
The invariant amplitude of
electromagnetic scattering off a fixed

91
00:06:38,734 --> 00:06:43,458
target is thus the integral over
the product between the transition current

92
00:06:43,458 --> 00:06:47,760
of the projectile and the electromagnetic
potential of the target.

93
00:06:48,830 --> 00:06:51,460
Note that this is a local interaction.

94
00:06:51,460 --> 00:06:56,240
Current and potential are defined
at the same point in space-time.

95
00:06:56,240 --> 00:06:58,355
But this point may be anywhere.

96
00:06:58,355 --> 00:07:02,780
Thus an integral over space-time
gives us the total amplitude.

97
00:07:02,780 --> 00:07:06,730
The electromagnetic current density
at work here looks like that for

98
00:07:06,730 --> 00:07:07,980
a free particle,

99
00:07:07,980 --> 00:07:10,780
except that the fields in the initial and

100
00:07:10,780 --> 00:07:15,620
final states are not the same
since there was an interaction.

101
00:07:15,620 --> 00:07:21,400
So the electromagnetic current density
interacts locally with the potential A^µ,

102
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:24,460
which we identify with the photon field.

103
00:07:24,460 --> 00:07:28,150
It remains to be understood how
this potential is generated.

104
00:07:28,150 --> 00:07:30,870
That is, how the photon is produced?

105
00:07:33,920 --> 00:07:38,150
For electromagnetic interaction,
the Maxwell equations tell us how

106
00:07:38,150 --> 00:07:43,370
the electromagnetic fields
are produced by charges and currents.

107
00:07:43,370 --> 00:07:48,392
Let us start by writing down
the homogeneous Maxwell equations in

108
00:07:48,392 --> 00:07:55,368
four-vector form, using the electromagnetic
field tensor F^munu. Translating into equations for

109
00:07:55,368 --> 00:08:01,810
the potential this gives four differential
equations for the four-potential A^nu.

110
00:08:01,810 --> 00:08:04,820
Using the invariance of the potential under

111
00:08:04,820 --> 00:08:09,292
the gauge transformations with
an arbitrary scalar field xi(x),

112
00:08:09,292 --> 00:08:14,290
we can always rearrange things so
that a A^µ has no divergence.

113
00:08:14,290 --> 00:08:16,950
We call this arrangement the Lorenz gauge.

114
00:08:16,950 --> 00:08:21,864
In this gauge the homogeneous Maxwell
equations are nothing else than four

115
00:08:21,864 --> 00:08:26,520
Klein-Gordon equations for
the components of the potential.

116
00:08:26,520 --> 00:08:30,520
But only three components
are independent of each other because

117
00:08:30,520 --> 00:08:32,530
of the gauge condition.

118
00:08:32,530 --> 00:08:37,680
This justifies that we consider
the homogeneous Maxwell equations

119
00:08:37,680 --> 00:08:42,140
as the equation of motion for
the photon, which is a vector boson and

120
00:08:42,140 --> 00:08:44,980
thus has three independent components.

121
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:52,015
In the presence of a current,
the equations become inhomogeneous.

122
00:08:52,015 --> 00:08:55,462
There is a source j_µ, on the right.

123
00:08:55,462 --> 00:09:00,085
We construct j_µ from the wave
function of the two other

124
00:09:00,085 --> 00:09:06,070
partners in the reaction,
the target particle b and its final state d.

125
00:09:06,070 --> 00:09:09,620
Their transition current
is the source of the field.

126
00:09:09,620 --> 00:09:14,029
The potential A_µ that corresponds to this
situation is proportional to this current

127
00:09:14,029 --> 00:09:18,204
density and inversely proportion to
the square of the transfered momentum q.

128
00:09:18,204 --> 00:09:23,263
The invariant amplitude thus corresponds
to the interaction between two currents.

129
00:09:23,263 --> 00:09:30,873
The intervening factor 1/q^2
is called the photon propagator.

130
00:09:30,873 --> 00:09:35,992
It described the probability
amplitude that a photon with

131
00:09:35,992 --> 00:09:41,840
four-momentum q is exchanged
between the two currents.

132
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:46,670
Since each current density brings in
a factor of e as a calling constant

133
00:09:46,670 --> 00:09:51,400
the amplitude is proportional
to e^2/q^2.

134
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:56,660
This process can be represented by
a feynman diagram as shown in this slide.

135
00:09:56,660 --> 00:10:00,640
These diagrams describe elementary
processes in a manner that is both

136
00:10:00,640 --> 00:10:01,940
elegant and intuitive.

137
00:10:03,010 --> 00:10:09,712
