139
00:10:13,806 --> 00:10:17,616
At the same time Feynman
diagrams are a prescription for

140
00:10:17,616 --> 00:10:20,523
the corresponding invariant amplitude.

141
00:10:20,523 --> 00:10:23,936
The vertices are characterized
by coupling constant,

142
00:10:23,936 --> 00:10:27,989
the electric charge in the case
of electromagnetic interactions,

143
00:10:27,989 --> 00:10:32,197
and an operator which describes
the properties of the interactions.

144
00:10:32,197 --> 00:10:37,058
The lines correspond to the propagators of particles,

145
00:10:37,058 --> 00:10:43,499
real ones for external lines,
virtual ones for internal lines connecting two vertices.

146
00:10:43,499 --> 00:10:49,184
The propagator 1/q^2 we
found for the photon is a special case for

147
00:10:49,184 --> 00:10:56,428
the more general one, which is 
1/(q^2 minus the square of the mass) 

148
00:10:56,428 --> 00:11:00,350
for massive intermediate vector bosons.

149
00:11:03,330 --> 00:11:08,990
If more than one elementary process
can cause a reaction we must

150
00:11:08,990 --> 00:11:13,170
either add the amplitudes or
the cross-sections.

151
00:11:13,170 --> 00:11:18,670
Because of the quantum nature of
the processes there exist two cases.

152
00:11:18,670 --> 00:11:22,977
If initial and final states of
the processes are indistinguishable,

153
00:11:22,977 --> 00:11:24,770
one must add the amplitudes.

154
00:11:24,770 --> 00:11:29,840
If there is an observable,
which allows in principle to distinguish

155
00:11:29,840 --> 00:11:35,320
different contributions, no matter if
it is actually measured or not,

156
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:41,780
these processes are distinguishable and
one must then sum the cross sections.

157
00:11:41,780 --> 00:11:45,100
The first case occurs of course for
example if one considers two

158
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:49,700
contribution of different orders
in the coupling constant.

159
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:53,840
The exchange of one of two photons
can intervene between the

160
00:11:53,840 --> 00:11:57,750
same initial final state as shown
in the picture in the left.

161
00:11:57,750 --> 00:12:02,456
If the two amplitudes M_1, M_2 describe
the two contributions, the square of

162
00:12:02,456 --> 00:12:05,694
the total amplitude, which leads
to the cross section,

163
00:12:05,694 --> 00:12:10,815
is then |M_1|^2 + |M_2|^2 + 2M_1M_2.

164
00:12:10,815 --> 00:12:16,335
is then |M_1|^2 + |M_2|^2 + 2M_1M_2.

165
00:12:16,335 --> 00:12:20,155
So this last term is an
interference term

166
00:12:20,155 --> 00:12:21,705
with appears in the probability.

167
00:12:21,705 --> 00:12:28,720
This is precisely not the case if
the processes are distinguishable in principle.

168
00:12:28,720 --> 00:12:32,180
Take the example of different
spin directions of the particles

169
00:12:32,180 --> 00:12:33,300
that interact.

170
00:12:33,300 --> 00:12:35,320
These are observable in principle.

171
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:41,410
As in the example shown in the right, 

172
00:12:41,410 --> 00:12:45,475
